(
Figs 1–3A, B
)

Rostral plate (
Fig. 1A
) quadrate, with 3 sharp triangular anterior projections, similar and subequal to each other; plate completely covering base of eyes, apex not extending to cornea; dorsal surface smooth.

Eyes extending beyond 3rd segment of antennular peduncle; cornea (
Fig. 1F
) subglobular but slightly expanded ventrally, oriented obliquely on stalk. Ophthalmic somite anterior margin transverse, straight, with small medioventral spine (
Fig. 1E
). Ocular scales (
Fig. 1A
) fused together into subquadrate lobe with obtusely bifurcate apex.

Antennular peduncle 0.47 CL. Lateral spines of antennular somite slender, directed anteriorly, almost reaching end of anterior rostral teeth. Antennal protopod (
Fig. 1G, H
) with 1 ventral papilla and 2 mesial papillae; antennal scale 0.26 CL.

Thoracic somites 6–8 lateral margins subtruncate to broadly rounded (
Fig. 1A
). Thoracic somite 8 sternal keel obsolete.

Pereiopods 1–3 (
Fig. 2C–E
) each with first protopod segment unarmed; endopods 2-segmented, distal segment subcircular (pereiopods 1 and 2), or elongate (pereiopod 3); penes well developed, overreaching distal end of pereiopod 3 protopodite.

Endopod of pleopod 1 (petasma; 
Fig. 2F, G
) with flattened and elongate tube process, hook process short, longer than broad, posterior endite simple, slightly overreaching hook process.

Pleonite 6 (
Fig. 1B–D
) smooth, unarmed dorsally; lateral margin almost straight, posterolateral angles spiniform, long; hook-shaped ventrolateral spine anterior to uropodal articulation; posterior margin of sternum with pair of spines.

Uropodal protopod (
Fig. 1B, D, I, J
) with 2 straight, ventrally smooth, primary spines, outer longer than inner; inner margin of protopod unarmed adjacent to endopod articulation; dorsal spine prominent, sharp. Exopod proximal segment outer margin with 5 graded movable spines with apices rounded, distalmost spine exceeding midlength of distal segment; distal margin with prominent ventral spine. Exopod distal segment ovate. Endopod elongate, distally rounded, maximum width on distal one-third of length, proximolateral setose dorsal sulcus feebly developed.

Colour.
Body (
Fig. 3A, B
) semitranslucent, with rostrum and carapace yellowish, pleon showing more distinct yellow internal median path, each segment with pair of yellow lateral transverse branches associated with bases of appendages. Body and appendages, including raptorial claw (
Fig. 2B
), irregularly black dotted, with larger but diffused submedian black spots on the carapace and dorsodistal parts of uropodal protopod (
Fig. 3A, B
).
